ype":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the French form of Latin or Italian  <b>Carolina</b> , a feminine derivative of <i>Carolus</i> (  see  Charles  ). This name was used by certain gentry families from the 17th century onwards, no doubt in honour of the Stuart kings named <i>Charles</i>. It was famously borne by  Lady Caroline Lamb  (  1785–1828 ), mistress of the poet  Lord Byron ."],"variants":[{"name":"Carolyn","meanings":["Altered form of   Caroline ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":92,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":101,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Caroline Matilda Sutton-Dudley was born in 1457, in Carlisle, Cumberland, England, her father, Sir Edmund Sutton, was 32 and her mother, Lady Joyce Tibetot, was 27. She married George Jodrell of Derbyshire in 1469, in Derby, Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in Derby, Derbyshire, England."},"et":{"1457–":"1457–Surnud","1451–Male":"1451–Surnud","1457–Female":"1457–Surnud","1460–1531":"1460–1531","1465–Female":"1465–Surnud","1454–Male":"1454–Surnud","1469–1523":"1469–1523","1425–1485":"1425–1485","1430–1485":"1430–1485","1451":"1451","1460":"1460","1459":"1459","1558":"1558","1469":"1469","1425":"1425","1457":"1457","1523":"1523","1454":"1454","1465":"1465","1531":"1531","1430":"1430","1485":"1485","1549":"1549","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England","Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Carlisle, Cumberland, England","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England"},"fi":{"1457–":"1457–Kuollut","1451–Male":"1